Here is an example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command, "ban":

```javascript
const { Client, Collection, Intents } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMessages, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMembers] });

client.once('ready', () => {
    console.log('Ready!');
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
        if (!interaction.memberPermissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
            return interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have permission to use this command.', ephemeral: true });
        }

        const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
        const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason');

        if (!user) {
            return interaction.reply({ content: 'You must specify a user to ban.', ephemeral: true });
        }

        try {
            await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason: reason || 'No reason provided.' });
            interaction.reply({ content: `User ${user.tag} has been banned.`, ephemeral: true });
        } catch (error) {
            interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error trying to ban that user.', ephemeral: true });
        }
    }
});

client.login('your-token-goes-here');
```

This bot will respond to the `/ban` slash command. The command takes one argument, `user`, which is the user to ban. It also takes an optional `reason` argument, which will be included in the ban message.

Please note that you need to replace 'your-token-goes-here' with your actual bot token.

Also, you need to create the slash command in the discord developer portal and invite the bot to your server.

You can check this link to know how to create a slash command: <https://discordjs.guide/interactions/creating-slash-commands.html#creating-a-command>

Here's a simple function that converts markdown text to HTML. This function only handles a small subset of markdown features, specifically bold and italic text. You can extend it to handle other markdown features as needed.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string& markdownText) {
    // Replace **bold** text with <b>bold</b>
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*{2}([^*]+)\\*{2}");
    markdownText = std::regex_replace(markdownText, boldRegex, "<b>$1</b>");

    // Replace *italic* text with <i>italic</i>
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*([^\\*]+)\\*");
    markdownText = std::regex_replace(markdownText, italicRegex, "<i>$1</i>");

    // Wrap the whole text in <p> tags
    markdownText = "<p>" + markdownText + "</p>";

    return markdownText;
}
```

Here's an example of how to use this function:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "Hello *world*, this is a **test**!";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```html
<p>Hello <i>world</i>, this is a <b>test</b>!</p>
```

